I"äO<p>When the Grammys announced the nominees on November 23, many in the music industry raised their eyebrows to see Taylor Swift and Jack Antonoff among those nominated for album of the year: not just for their album â€œEvermoreâ€, but also for co-writing Olivia Rodrigoâ€™s â€œSour.â€ Considering that neither Swift nor Antonoff or Annie Clark (whoâ€™s collaborated with Swift in the past and is also nominated for â€œSourâ€) actively wrote any Rodrigoâ€™s â€œSourâ€, many were perplexed by the Academyâ€™s nod to Swift and her collaborators. On Sunday night the Recording Academy, the entity responsible for the Grammy awards, <a href="https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/taylor-swift-olivia-rodrigo-grammy-2022-nomination-adjustment-1235005995/">rectified the mistake</a>, citing a mistake in paperwork. The Recording Academyâ€™s confusion is yet another chapter in a long story about the difference between copyright infringement and paying proper homage to the artistic influences that came before. According to analysis of case data, musical copyright cases have been increasing in frequency over the past decade with significant increases in the past five years, raising increasing complex questions about musical ownership in the 21st century.</p>

<p>For Rodrigo, the controversy over her alleged theft culminated in September, when she <a href="https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/benhenry/olivia-rodrigo-paramore-good-4-u-taylor-swift-deja-vu">made headlines by giving up millions in royalties</a> through granting retroactive songwriting credit to Taylor Swift for her song â€œdÃ©jÃ  vuâ€. Rodrigo announced the additional credits after months of speculation online and a couple of a little too YouTube perfect mashups caused by many fans to point out that â€œdÃ©jÃ  vuâ€ bore a strong resemblance to Swiftâ€™s â€œCruel Summerâ€, accusing the singer of artistic theft.</p>

<p>While some applauded Rodrigoâ€™s move (one Tik-Toker even <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@luxxuryxx/video/7000462584503667973?referer_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dazeddigital.com%2F&amp;referer_video_id=7000462584503667973&amp;refer=embed&amp;is_copy_url=1&amp;is_from_webapp=v1">encouraged his followers to â€œkeep narkingâ€</a>, many musical experts raised concerns on Rodrigoâ€™s crediting artists who had no active part of the songwriting process as â€˜songwritersâ€™. Some wondered if Rodrigoâ€™s acknowledgment that Taylor Swift was one of her largest musical influences in multiple interviews was just as responsible for the accusations of stealing as the actual musical similarities.
This idea of influence seems to be the true catch in the case of Rodrigoâ€™s transgressions. Reporting on Rodrigoâ€™s use of yelling vocals in the Bridge of â€œdÃ©jÃ  vuâ€ (similar vocals in Swiftâ€™s â€œCruel Summerâ€) is almost always mentioned in connection with Rodrigoâ€™s admittance in an interview that Swift was one of her greatest influences and inspirations. As Adam Neely, a bassist and YouTube music educator <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qX7a2p5_JsM&amp;t=376s">put it in his video on the Rodrigo controversy</a>: â€œâ€¦ Olivia Rodrigo was wearing her influence on her sleeve just a little too brightly for some folks.â€  This strategy, of using artistsâ€™ own admittance of influence as evidence for musical theft, is eerily similar to one employed by the Gaye family in 2015 in the infamous court case surrounding Pharrell Williams and Robin Thickeâ€™s song â€œBlurred Linesâ€.</p>

<h2 id="musical-copyright-in-the-courts">Musical Copyright in the Courts</h2>
<p>In 2015 the Gaye estate won their copyright case against Williams and Thicke for infringement on Marvin Gayeâ€™s 1977 song â€œGot to Give it Upâ€. The Gaye Estateâ€™s complaint dedicates several pages to Thickeâ€™s long proclaimed admiration of Gayeâ€™s, citing his homage to the R&amp;B legend as the introductory evidence that the artist couldâ€™ve committed copyright infringement. The Gaye estate then specifically claimed that the 2013 hit â€œBlurred Linesâ€ copied <a href="https://blogs.law.gwu.edu/mcir/case/pharrell-williams-et-al-v-frankie-gaye-et-al/">â€œsignature phrase, vocal hook, backupâ€¦â€</a> from Marvin Gayeâ€™s original.
The big hitch with that complaint? <a href="https://www.rollingstone.com/pro/features/music-copyright-lawsuits-chilling-effect-935310/">Until that point</a>, such secondary musical elements (i.e., elements other than melody, harmony, and rhythm) were not subject to copyright. When the Gayeâ€™s won their case in 2015 (although appeals would last till 2018), they essentially won in copywriting a musical vibe, rather than just a specific melody or musical element. Previously, musical copyright protected what was understood to be ideas in artistic expression, not the expression themselves.</p>

<p>As Peter Jaszi, Professor Emeritus at American University College of Law, explained, â€œThe standard line on that is that copyright in musicâ€¦doesnâ€™t protect the style. Anyone can try to write like Hemmingway and even if theyâ€™re very successful the Hemmingway estate doesnâ€™t have any basis on which to sue them as long as they use their own dialogue and their own characters â€¦.â€ The â€œBlurred Linesâ€ case pushed against that limitation, claiming that there was more to music than just the core melodies. The 2015 court case ushered in an era of fear into the music industry as labels suddenly began to question what exactly would send them to court while the outcome in court was ultimately much harder to predict.</p>

<p>The music industry has been on edge ever since â€œBlurred Linesâ€, concerned that the affirmative ruling for the plaintiffs will set a new precedent for copyright infringement in the courts. However, according to an analysis of data compiled from GW Law Schoolâ€™s Musical Copyright Resource, the concerns seem to be largely unfounded, at least as far as the courts are concerned. However, itâ€™s the reaction of the public which seems to be most intriguing.</p>

<p>Before the Blurred Lines case, the average number of cases between 2010-2015 was four cases a year. After the court decision in 2015, the average number of cases between 2016-2021 increased to 13,  more than tripling previous yearsâ€™ average.</p>

