<p>Itâ€™s hard to necessarily claim correlation but, notably, the extreme spike falls almost exactly on the date that â€œBlurred Linesâ€ went to court.</p>

<p>Charles Cronin, Project Director of the GW Law Schools Musical Copyright Resource who began the project in the 1980s, believes this uptick is the result of ploys for cash by musicians and lawyers alike. â€œAnd theseâ€¦ plaintiffs typically, are represented by attorneys who are working on a contingency fee basis, which means they will get aâ€¦ portion of any settlement or award, that results from the ultimate disposition of the case. And this raises, I think, the very strong possibility, if not probability, that many of these cases are brought as simply a means of shaking down a successful defendant to get a handout to get them to go away,â€ Cronin said.</p>

<p>Looking at the ways courts have decided in recent years Croninâ€™s suspicion may not be unfounded, at least initially. In 2016, 45% percent of the cases put before the court were settled between the plaintiffs and defendants, often for undisclosed amounts of money. Thatâ€™s opposed to less than one percent in 2015. Led Zeppelin and Katy Perryâ€™s respective wins in appeals this year have <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/arts/music/blurred-lines-led-zeppelin-copyright.html">many breathing a sigh of relief</a>, but itâ€™s yet to be seen if cases will ever return to previous levels.</p>

<p>When Jaszi discussed this uptick he said, â€œI cannot prove this but I suspect that the uptick in filings that you observed is a function of that shared belief thatâ€¦ â€œBlurred Linesâ€ was going to be the beginning of a new dispensation on music copyright. Of course, it wasnâ€™t.â€ Thatâ€™s the thing, â€œBlurred Linesâ€ doesnâ€™t look to have changed the way courts decide things very much at all.</p>

